---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="A Note On Precedent" section={7}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={7}
      title="A Note On Precedent"
      meta="~300 words + closing"
    />

    <p>
      Nothing in this document is new. The argument for restraint appears
      in every serious writing on typography and print design. The argument
      for warmth appears in every serious writing on reading environments.
      The argument for behavioral attention appears in every serious writing
      on human-computer interaction. What's new is the context — applying
      these ideas to a conversational medium that didn't exist until recently.
    </p>

    <p>
      iA Writer got there first, in the sense that Oliver Reichenstein
      spent a decade arguing, against considerable market pressure, that
      a writing tool should look like a piece of paper and behave like one. Early Instapaper made the same argument about reading:
      strip everything except the words. The best of print design — from
      Jan Tschichold's asymmetric typography to Robert Bringhurst's grid —
      makes the argument about space and proportion as the fundamental
      materials of communication.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      What's new is applying these ideas to a conversational medium.
      The interface recedes so the conversation can be the product.
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      The conversational medium changes one thing: the reader is also the
      writer. The same interface that needs to be calm enough to read in
      needs to be inviting enough to write in. The same column that
      constrains line length for comprehension needs to feel generous at
      the input. This is the specific tension that conversational design
      has to resolve — and that the preceding sections have tried to address,
      one layer at a time.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Standing on shoulders">
      These interfaces deserve acknowledgment: iA Writer, Instapaper (2009–2013),
      Readability, Ulysses, Bear, and the long tradition of typographic
      thinking that underlies them. The ideas here are not original — the
      application is.
    </Annotation>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <div class="closing">
      <div class="closing-rule"></div>
      <h2 class="closing-heading">The One Question</h2>
      <p>
        Before shipping any UI element, ask: does this help the user think,
        or does it remind them they're using software?
      </p>
      <p>
        If the answer is the latter — cut it. If you can't cut it, hide it.
        If you can't hide it, earn its presence through craft so complete
        that it becomes invisible anyway.
      </p>
      <p>
        The goal isn't an empty screen. The goal is a screen so full of
        the right thing that there's no room for anything else to compete.
        Thought is the product. Everything else is infrastructure.
      </p>
      <a href={base} class="closing-return">← Return to start</a>
    </div>

  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .closing {
    margin-top: var(--sp-16);
    padding-top: var(--sp-8);
  }

  .closing-rule {
    width: 48px;
    height: 2px;
    background: var(--terra-300);
    border-radius: 2px;
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-6);
  }

  .closing-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: var(--text-h2);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--ink-900);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-6);
  }

  .closing :global(p) {
    margin-bottom: 1.4em;
  }

  .closing-return {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: var(--sp-8);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--terra-600);
    text-decoration: none;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    transition: color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-soft);
  }

  .closing-return:hover {
    color: var(--terra-800);
  }
</style>
